            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Alexei Volkov is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog-laced avenues and his family\u2019s Soviet past. The only child of a stoic engineer father and a librarian mother who fled Leningrad in the late 1970s, Alexei was raised in the Richmond District on stories of a world left behind. His father, while employed by a municipal utility, was a craftsman at heart, filling their small home with meticulously hand-carved wooden toys and repaired furniture. It was from him that Alexei learned the language of wood: its grain, its scent, its memory.\n\nInitially, Alexei channeled this inherited skill into fine art, pursuing a graduate degree in sculpture. He created large, abstract forms from reclaimed lumber and steel, but felt a growing disconnect between his work and its purpose. The turning point came during his final year, when he restored a dilapidated Victorian-era settee found in a dumpster. The process of bringing the piece back to life\u2014honoring the original maker\u2019s intent while mending the damages of time\u2014felt more profound than any abstract sculpture he had ever made. He realized his calling wasn't in creating new things, but in preserving the beautiful and useful things that already existed.\n\nAfter graduating, he apprenticed with an old Italian restorer in North Beach before opening his own small shop, \"Volkov Restoration,\" in a cozy Hayes Valley storefront. His apartment is directly above the shop, making his 0.4-mile commute a simple walk downstairs. His days are a ritual of smells\u2014turpentine, beeswax, and fresh coffee from the cafe next door. He spends hours meticulously re-caning chairs or stabilizing the veneer on a Biedermeier cabinet.\n\nSocially, Alexei maintains a small, tight-knit circle of friends, mostly other local artisans and shopkeepers. His life is quiet and deliberate. He has had relationships, but his singular focus on his craft has often taken precedence. His dream isn\u2019t of wealth, but of legacy. He hopes to one day acquire and restore a piece by a master craftsman like Wharton Esherick, and perhaps find an apprentice to whom he can pass on his skills. For Alexei, each restored piece of furniture is a conversation with the past, and in his small Hayes Valley workshop, he is San Francisco\u2019s dedicated custodian of stories told in wood."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, the Richmond fog thick outside. His father took a small block of pine and placed Alexei\u2019s hand upon it, tracing the lines of the grain with his son's finger. \u201cEvery piece tells you where it wants to go, Alyosha,\u201d he\u2019d murmured in Russian. It wasn\u2019t a lesson in woodworking, but in listening. In that moment, surrounded by the scent of sawdust, Alexei felt the wood\u2019s history connect to his own. It was a language of patience and memory that would become his native tongue.\n\n2.\nThe final year of his MFA felt hollow until he found the derelict Victorian settee. Late one night in the studio, he abandoned his abstract sculpture and ran his hand over the settee\u2019s splintered arm. He felt the ghost of the original craftsman\u2019s intent. A profound clarity washed over him; his purpose wasn\u2019t to impose his own voice, but to amplify the voices of the past. Restoring that single piece felt more honest and vital than any art he had ever created. It was an act of service, not ego.\n\n3.\nHis apprenticeship under Mr. Bellini in North Beach was mostly silence and watching. The old man finally handed him a tiny, warped piece of satinwood inlay from a priceless bureau. \u201cYou fix,\u201d he grunted. For two days, Alexei worked, his breath held. When he slid the repaired piece back into place, flush and seamless, Bellini simply nodded once. That single, silent gesture of approval felt more validating than his entire graduate degree. He was no longer a student; he was a restorer in a long, trusted line.\n\n4.\nHe remembers Sarah\u2019s frustration, her hands on her hips in his small apartment. \u201cIt\u2019s just a chair, Alexei.\u201d But it wasn\u2019t. It was a century-old conversation he was trying to save from oblivion. In her eyes, he saw the life he was supposed to want\u2014weekends away, social dinners. In the stubborn, broken spindle in his hands, he saw the life he needed. The relationship ended soon after, a quiet sacrifice laid at the altar of his craft, leaving a clean, sorrowful joint in his memory.\n\n5.\nThe day he opened Volkov Restoration, he stood alone in the empty Hayes Valley storefront. The air smelled of fresh paint and possibility. Before anything else, he placed his father\u2019s old jointer plane on the workbench. It wasn\u2019t for use, but for presence. As the morning light hit the tool\u2019s worn wooden handle, he felt his father\u2019s quiet pride and the generations of craftsmen before him. This wasn't just a shop; it was an anchor, a promise, and the start of his own story."
